!! Jesus Rejected at Nazareth (4:16-30)
Jesus reads and quotes Isaiah 61 in the Synagogue. This chapter recaps the Lord's plans (in context of the book of Isaiah, this is where God reveals His plans.)

Jesus interesting stops at the half of verse 2 in Isaiah because the second half talks about judgement (which Jesus will do in the future but not in this current timeline).


!!! The Audience's Doubt

<<<
And he said to them, "Doubtless you will quote to me this proverb, 'Physician, heal yourself.' What we have heard you did at Capernaum, do here in your hometown as well."
<<<
''Luke 4:23''

We see that in response, the people at the synagogue started to doubt Jesus and His proclamation. The people doubt Jesus' position by saying "Is not this Joseph's son?" Luke 4:22.

Jesus notes that their heart was wrong, stating that the people were doubting Christ and requiring that He proves Himself. "What we have heard you did at Capernaum, do here in your hometown as well." Isn't this testing Jesus? Just in verse 12 we see that Jesus knew he should not tempt God and had proven Himself worthy of resisting this temptation. The audience had failed.

!!! The Story of Elijah

<<<
And he said, “Truly, I say to you, no prophet is acceptable in his hometown.
<<<
Luke 4:24

Jesus had already known that He would be rejected because He was in His hometwon. He recounts Elijah and Sidon as an illustration to this principle.

Elijah was rejected by the Israelites so he was sent to Sidon. Then again Elisha in Syria.

These stories help illuminate both Jesus statement that "no prophet is acceptable in his hometown" but also the fact that the Israelites had had a history of not listening to God. After hearing Jesus tell this story, this enraged the synagogue (v28) since, at that time, the Israelites thought they were the chosen people who will be delivered by God. A sense of nationalistic pride. But Jesus reminded them of their failures and their hard hearted past.

